data.name: SETUP_CredentialStore
data.value: The credential store is used to securely store passwords. In this application, three basic stores are available: - Windows Credential Store: credentials are saved for the current user in the Generic Credentials section. You can access this store from the Control Panel. - Environment variables: credentials are stored in a user-level environment variable. - Application configuration file: credentials will be stored in the AppSettings section of AIChessDB.exe.config. Anyone with access to this file will be able to see them. In any case, you will have to enter a name for the credential. You will be asked to create a credential for the OpenAI API key. You will also be asked to create credentials for the database connection strings, since they contain passwords and access data.

data.name: SETUP_APIKey
data.value: AI assistants work through an API manager. Each API manager requires a key to operate. Enter an identifying name for the key and its actual value, provided by the API provider. In the configuration files, only the key name will be stored. The actual key will be saved in the credential manager selected in the previous step.

data.name: SETUP_ConnectionString
data.value: This application works with a database. Before continuing with the setup, you must ensure that the database is installed and accessible from this computer. The database can be hosted on an Oracle, SQL Server, or MySQL server. To connect, you need to create at least one connection string, although several can be created for the same server or for different servers. Connection strings always require the following data: - Server name or IP address (and port, if not using the default one). - Username to access the database. - User password. In MySQL and SQL Server, you must also specify the database or schema where the data resides.

data.name: SETUP_Assistants
data.value: This is an application assisted by AI agents. By default, three assistants must be created with different functions: - Help the user with the use of the application. - Help the user with configuration. - Play chess with the user and comment on and analyze existing games. Depending on the type of assistant you select, objects will be created in the account of the chosen AI provider. A document store will also be created for each of these assistants, where the initial documentation will be stored. You can change the names, the documentation, and add new assistants once the application is configured.

data.name: MSG_SystemToUser
data.value:
### Welcome to AIChessDB
This application combines **a chess games database** with **AI assistants** that guide you through its use. From the console, you can ask the assistants to help you with:
- **Importing games in PGN format** into the database. - **Searching existing games** with filters by players, positions, or moves. - **Creating or editing a game** manually. - **Replaying games** on an interactive board with moves and comments.
You can also ask them to **explain and point out the buttons and elements of the forms**, so you can better understand how each part of the application works. In addition, the console toolbar includes a dropdown menu with quick access to the main forms. By default, there are those three assistants: - **{0}**: Help the user with the use of the application. - **{1}**: Help the user with configuration. - **{2}**: Play chess with the user and comment on and analyze existing games.
Type your first request in the console, for example: **"Import a PGN file"** or **"Open the game search form"**, and let the assistants do the rest.
